## State Management Mapping

| React | Vue 3 (`<script setup>`) |
|-------|--------------------------|
| `useState(value)` | `ref(value)` (access via `.value` in JS, direct in template) |
| `useState([])` | `ref([])` or `reactive([])` |
| `useState({})` | `reactive({})` (no `.value` needed) |
| `useMemo(fn, [deps])` | `computed(() => ...)` |
| `useEffect(fn, [])` | `onMounted(() => ...)` |
| `useEffect(fn, [dep])` | `watch(dep, fn)` |
| `useEffect(fn, [a, b])` | `watchEffect(() => ...)` or `watch([a, b], fn)` |
| `useCallback(fn, [])` | Plain function (no memoization needed by default) |
| `useRef(null)` | `ref(null)` (template refs work the same way) |

### ref vs reactive

```js
// ref — for primitives and single values
const count = ref(0);
count.value++; // access via .value in <script>
// In template: {{ count }} (no .value)

// reactive — for objects/arrays (avoid for primitives)
const form = reactive({ name: '', email: '' });
form.name = 'John'; // no .value needed
```

